{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a295ac3-2469-4ca3-9e34-adfcd22b66db","content":"Use conditional compilation with `#if` directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach platform-specific class lives under `Platforms/<platform>/` and is only compiled for its target (the folder-based targeting in the `.csproj` handles this automatically).\n\n**Alternative (no `#if`):** Use partial classes or the `[assembly: Dependency(...)]` pattern with a single registration pointing to a shared partial class that has platform-specific implementations in each `Platforms/` folder. But the `#if` approach above is the most straightforward and commonly used in MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6a276f00-bd3b-4607-a8ea-11b3d35cbd24","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection — specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` interface in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task in the repository.","outputTokens":359,"requestId":"0823:1ED665:ABA2A5:C63E4F:69F2A9EC"},"id":"b84b376f-123a-456e-b3bf-a72aa800d64a","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:01:41.391Z","parentId":"137d7b3b-3b6a-4a42-ae84-78fffc8a2c34"}
